      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Traffic Solution, But Also a Problem</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rita Krich letter on April 1 editorial holds toll system in parts of Manhattan would increase divide between rich, middle class and poor</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Gridlock's Other Toll'' (editorial, April 1):</p>
        <p>I am puzzled as to why every solution to the traffic problem in Manhattan increases the divide between the rich and middle class and poor of our city. It is the rich who will benefit from a fee system.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Gridlock's Other Toll'' (editorial, April 1):</p>
        <p>I am puzzled as to why every solution to the traffic problem in Manhattan increases the divide between the rich and middle class and poor of our city. It is the rich who will benefit from a fee system.</p>
        <p>It will not matter to them if they have to pay $10 each time they wish to drive into the city.</p>
        <p>It will not matter to them if the cabs they use cost a great deal more. The rich will still use all the cultural activities and the shopping while using their limos and cars.</p>
        <p>What about the rest of us? Will there be provision for the less able and handicapped to come into the city for a museum or theater experience or doctor's appointment? Will there be consideration for the many who drive into Manhattan because they cannot climb the stairs of the transit system? Can our already crowded public rail and bus system absorb the addition of thousands of users?</p>
        <p>Rita Krich  Bayside, Queens</p>
      </block>
